post_title: Buying/Renting Property In Humboldt? Get It Checked For Bedbugs.
post_text:
If you've been thinking about investing, or living, in Humboldt County, there's something you ought to know.
 Humboldt County has bedbugs.
 Sure, bedbugs are everywhere.
 But they flourish in certain conditions. Poverty, crowding, sloth, and illiteracy, to name a few. You'll find all four in Humboldt County.
 Now, you might think this doesn't affect you. You're a wealthy investor, looking for a summer home - or a college student, just here for a few years. None of your friends has bedbugs. Right?
 However, you have no idea what the history of your property is. It might have been a rental, for instance. If you're a student, it's almost guaranteed.
 Did you know that bedbugs can go up to 300 days without feeding?
 And even if your property wasn't a rental, do you know who's been inside your house? Wages in Humboldt County are purposefully held at just above poverty levels, for the convenience of the wealthy amongst us ... but, unless you are so wealthy as to be able to provide a home for your housekeepers and your groundskeepers, the odds are pretty good that your hired help are living with the rest of the huddled masses.
 And who knows what they've tracked into your house?
 Last, but not least ... the phrases 'new carpets' and 'new flooring' need to be regarded with dread.
 Because you need to ask yourself - what's hidden underneath?
 If the last resident of the house had bedbugs, and the real estate agent was clueless, and slapped on a new coat of paint and threw down a cheap carpet ... then you'll have bedbugs, too, about three or four months after you move in ... and you'll spend a lot of time, blaming yourself - before you realize that you have been reamed, by your friends, and neighbors, here in Humboldt County.
 I speak from experience.
 If I were going to buy, or rent, a residential space, in Humboldt County I would now insist on a clause affirming that if bedbugs were discovered in the house any time during the first year after purchase, that the seller would assume full responsibility for correcting the problem - and all expenses associated with the correction.
 Because, you know ... that's how they do it, in other civilized countries.
 If I were a student - or a parent of a student - I would engage in a little diligence, and insist on seeing some sort of written certification from someone whom I could independently contact - just to be sure that the room, and the building, that my best and brightest was living in, was actually clean.
 I would insist on accountability - I would want to know whom I could speak to and hold accountable, if things were not as they were represented.
 I wouldn't go on hearsay. A pound of hearsay - and five dollars - will buy you a cup of coffee, here in North America, these days.
 Food for thought.
 PS: One of the clever ways that property owners and managers have come up with, to conceal bedbug infestations, is to fill in the crevices.
 Inside the house, take a close look at the doorways, and the door frames.
 There should be a visible crevice between the wooden frame and the plaster of the wall, all around the door - even if the door, and the frame, and the wall, have been repainted.
 If the crevices have been systematically filled in ... then the odds are pretty good that the property has previously been infested by bed bugs.
